article.description: Katie Smith made two free throws with 6.2 seconds left, and the Minnesota Lynx withstood New York's late run to beat the Liberty 64-60 Friday night.
article.headline: Minnesota snaps five-game road losing streak
article.linkText: Lynx hold off late Liberty rally
article.story:
NEW YORK (AP) -- Even without a big scoring night, Katie Smith
played a major role in the final seconds for the Minnesota Lynx.

Smith found Vanessa Hayden on a pick-and-roll with 12.8 seconds
left, then hit two free throws with 6½ seconds late left and the
Lynx withstood New York's late run to beat the Liberty 64-60 Friday
night.

"Getting the ball in my hands is going to draw a little bit of
a crowd," Smith said. "Vanessa set a good pick and she was able
to roll to the hole and I got it to her and she finished."

Hayden had 14 points and nine rebounds, Svetlana Abrosimova
scored 11 points and Nicole Ohlde and Smith added 10 each for
Minnesota (10-8), which won its second straight and snapped a
five-game road losing streak.

"We moved the ball well," Smith said. "We made them work for
whatever they got, we rebounded the ball well. It was a good effort
on both ends."

Crystal Robinson scored 13 points, Ann Wauters had 12 and
Shameka Christon 10 to lead the Liberty (8-8), who had their
three-game winning streak end.

After Tamika Williams' basket stretched Minnesota's lead to
58-50 lead with 5:05 remaining, Christon scored seven points during
the Liberty's 8-0 run and hit the tying jumper with 2:16 remaining.

Amber Jacobs and Williams both hit a free throw to give the Lynx
a 60-58 lead with 57.2 seconds left. Robinson missed a 3 for New
York 17 seconds later, and Hayden's layup gave Minnesota a
four-point lead.

"It was a huge basket, and Katie was able to find Vanessa with
the attention she draws," Lynx coach Suzie McConnell Serio said.
"We want the ball in (Katie's) hands, to be on the free-throw line
in late-game situations."

Becky Hammon's two free throws with 9.8 seconds left cut the
Liberty's deficit to 62-60. Smith, who became the first woman to
score 5,000 career points in professional basketball two nights
earlier, then made her foul shots 3.5 seconds later to seal the
Lynx's win.

"Our defense just wasn't that great tonight," Robinson said.
"We go through spurts where we don't rebound the ball well. On
this team, it's a team effort. Everyone has to do their share and
rebound the ball. We didn't rebound the ball well, and we didn't
defend."

Smith's 3-pointer near the midpoint of the second half stretched
Minnesota's lead to game-high 11 points at 52-42.

New York began slowly chipping away, with Wauters' reverse layup
cutting the deficit to 56-50 with 5:30 remaining.

"Defensively, we stuck ourselves in a hole," Hammon said.
"Everytime we made little runs, they came back and hit shots. We
can't afford to do that on our own court."

Minnesota outrebounded New York 33-20, and had a 40-28 advantage
in points in the paint. The Lynx also committed 17 turnovers,
leading to 22 points for the Liberty.

"Rebounding the ball was an emphasis coming in and we took
advantage of that tonight," McConnell Serio said. "Teams continue
to capitalize on our turnovers, so that's always an area of
concern. We knew they were capable of making a run, but we kept our
composure and we were able to withstand that run and come back and
win the game."

Minnesota, playing its fourth straight in stretch of seven
consecutive games against Eastern Conference teams, led 34-28 at
the break. Hayden scored 10 points on 5-for-9 shooting and
Abrosimova added eight points in the period to lead the Lynx.

The Liberty, who dropped 4 1/2 games behind first-place Connecticut
in the East, play their next four on the road against Seattle,
Phoenix, Sacramento and Minnesota.
